class Solution {
    public long maximumScoreAfterOperations(int[][] edges, int[] values) {
        List<Integer>[] g = new ArrayList[values.length];
        Arrays.setAll(g, e -> new ArrayList<>());
        g[0].add(-1);
        for (int[] e : edges) {
            int x = e[0], y = e[1];
            g[x].add(y);
            g[y].add(x);
        }
        long ans = 0;
        for (int v : values) {
            ans += v;
        }
        return dfs(0, -1, g, values);
    }

    private long dfs(int x, int fa, List<Integer>[] g, int[] values) {
        if (g[x].size() == 1) {
            return values[x];
        }
        long loss = 0;
        for (int y : g[x]) {
            if (y != fa) {
                loss += dfs(y, x, g, values);
            }
        }
        return Math.min(values[x], loss);
    }
}
```

This code works by creating an adjacency list representation of the tree. The function dfs is used to traverse the tree and calculate the minimum value at each node that could be subtracted from the total sum of values to make the tree healthy. The function maximumScoreAfterOperations then returns the sum of values minus the total minimum value calculated by dfs.

The time complexity of this code is O(n), where n is the number of nodes in the tree. This is because each node is visited and processed once in the dfs function. The space complexity is also O(n) as the space required is proportional to the number of nodes in the tree.

Note: The problem statement is a bit confusing because it mentions the tree being "healthy" but does not provide specific conditions for it. I assume that by "healthy" it means that the sum of values on the path from the root to any leaf node is different than zero. If this is not the case, the solution would need to be adjusted accordingly

