A: You need to compare the maximum number of a group of numbers with the minimum number of a next group of numbers. If the maximum number of a group is smaller than the minimum number of the next group, then you can not sort the array.

So the line of code to fill in the blank in the given code should be:

curGroupMax = Math.max(curGroupMax, num);

Complete code:

```java
class Solution {
    public boolean canSortArray(int[] nums) {
        int lastCnt = 0;
        int lastGroupMax = 0;
        int curGroupMax = 0;
        for (int num : nums) {
            int curCnt = Integer.bitCount(num);
            if (curCnt == lastCnt) {
                curGroupMax = Math.max(curGroupMax, num);
            } else {
                if (num < lastGroupMax) {
                    return false;
                }
                lastCnt = curCnt;
                lastGroupMax = curGroupMax;
                curGroupMax = num;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
}
```

In this code, we maintain a group with the same number of set bits (lastCnt). We keep updating the maximum number in this group (curGroupMax). And for the next group, we compare the maximum number of the current group with the minimum number of the next group (lastGroupMax). If the maximum number of the current group is smaller, we return false; else we continue to the next group.
If we can finish the loop without returning false, we return true.

This is because if there are two groups with the same number of set bits, we can swap the elements within these groups. If the maximum number of the current group is smaller than the minimum number of the next group, we cannot sort the array with the swaps.

So, we need to make sure the maximum number of the current group is greater than or equal to the minimum number of the next group.

Please note that the problem is asking to return true if the array can be sorted, not if it can be rearranged to be sorted.

